    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1961-04-19T02:01:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1961-04-19T02:01:00-05:00" n="138"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d138">
                <head>138. Telegram From the Commander in Chief, Atlantic (<persName
                        corresp="#p_DARL1" type="from">Dennison</persName>) to the Chief of Naval
                    Operations (<persName corresp="#p_BAAA1" type="to">Burke</persName>)<note n="0"
                        type="source" xml:id="d138fn0">Source: Naval Historical Center, Area Files,
                        Bumpy Road Materials. Top Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Norfolk</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1961-04-19T02:01:00-05:00">April 19, 1961, 2:01 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>190701Z. Exclusive for <persName corresp="#p_BAAA1">Admiral Burke</persName> from
                        <persName corresp="#p_DARL1">Dennison</persName>.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>A.</label>
                    <item>Your 190137Z.<note n="1" xml:id="d138fn1">
                            <ref target="#d133">Document 133</ref>.</note>
                    </item>
                    <label>B.</label>
                    <item>My 190627Z.<note n="2" xml:id="d138fn2">
                            <ref target="#d137">Document 137</ref>.</note>
                        <list>
                            <label>1.</label>
                            <item>See Ref B to <gloss target="#t_CTG1">CTG</gloss> 81.8 <gloss
                                    target="#t_info1">info</gloss>
                                <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>.</item>
                            <label>2.</label>
                            <item>Evacuation of wounded is completely out of the question without
                                overt involvement of US forces. Furthermore, I know of no haven in
                                    <pb facs="0321" n="289" xml:id="pg_289"/> some place
                                “inaccessible to news hawks.” Evacuation either by day or night is a
                                fantastically unrealistic project unless I am permitted to put
                                sufficient force ashore, with air and gunfire support from the sea,
                                to provide a beach head. Alternative would be for <gloss
                                    target="#t_CEF1">CEF</gloss> ships to bring wounded from beach
                                to sea.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
